&gt; I had not previously realised that this was a hotly debated 
&gt; subject, but I can think of at least one example of a test 
&gt; that should have at least two assertion in it: the equals() method.

I&#39;m not necessarily disagreeing with you but I think it is always
possible to re-write the test so it only has one assertion in it.  For
example:

public class TestSomeObectEquals extends TestCase
{
    private SomeObject m_a = null;
    private SomeObject m_b = null;

    public void setUp()
    {
        m_a = new SomeObject(&quot;abc&quot;);
        m_b = new someObject(&quot;abc&quot;);
    }

    public void testSymmetryAB()
    {
        assertTrue(&quot;Symmetry test a == b failed.&quot;, m_a.equals(m_b));
    }

    public void testSymmetryBA()
    {
        assertTrue(&quot;Symmetry test b == a failed.&quot;, m_b.equals(m_a));
    }
}

I think better names could be used but you get the idea....  As long as
your tests stay focused and are easy to understand I don&#39;t think it
really matters how many assertions the test contains.  For example:
    public void testSymmetry()
    {
        assertTrue(&quot;Symmetry test a == b failed.&quot;, m_a.equals(m_b));
        assertTrue(&quot;Symmetry test b == a failed.&quot;, m_b.equals(m_a));    
    }
Is just as easy to read as when each assertion was in its own method in
my opinion.


&gt; Also, what about edge-conditions? 

Each edge condition could be in its own test method.  

Kris


